3. Initialize the DB:

```sh
sudo postgresql-setup initdb
```

4. Add the PostgreSQL service to system startup and check status:

```sh
sudo systemctl start postgresql
sudo systemctl enable postgresql
sudo systemctl status postgresql
```

5. Login to the database:

```sh
sudo -u postgres psql
```

6. Set new password:

```sh
ALTER USER postgres PASSWORD 'myPassword';
\q
```

By default the remote PostgreSQL connection is disabled. You need to add the following configuration to enable remote connectivity.

7. Enable Remote Connection For PostgreSQL on Amazon Linux

```sh
sudo nano /var/lib/pgsql/data/postgresql.conf
```

Locate the line that starts with “listen_addresses“. Uncomment and change it to “listen_addresses = ‘*’“. This will allow connections from any IP address.

8. Edit pg_hba.conf

```sh
sudo nano /var/lib/pgsql/data/pg_hba.conf
```

Add the following to the end of the file to allow client connections to all databases.

```sh
host    all          all            0.0.0.0/0  md5
```

9. To apply all the changes, restart the PostgreSQL service using the following command.

```sh
sudo systemctl restart postgresql
```

2. Install the PostgreSQL server on the EC2 Instance:

```sh
sudo amazon-linux-extras enable postgresql14

sudo yum install postgresql-server -y
```

3. Connect to the DB instance:

```sh
psql --host=endpoint --port=5432 --dbname=postgres --username=postgres
